"# Chapter 16 — Value Verification

Fifteen chapters of *do it right*. This chapter is *check that you
did it right*. If the check fires you get a chance to fix things
before your users do.

## What to verify

Three levels.

**Level 1 — Shape.** Is this value the shape the function expects?
Money? Instant? Duration? Ranged? Present? These are cheap tests
you can run at every function boundary.

**Level 2 — Constraint.** Is the value inside the constraints the
value is supposed to satisfy? Money non-negative for prices?
Percentage between 0 and 100? Timestamp not in the future? These
are per-domain rules.

**Level 3 — Invariant.** Is a *property of the whole computation*
still true? Total after allocation equals total before? Sum of line
items equals grand total? Balance after transfer equals balance
before minus amount? These are the properties that catch bugs
between correct components.

DO: verify at three levels — shape at every boundary, constraint
where the domain rules bite, invariant at the top of the computation.
DON'T: skip invariants because the individual pieces are tested.
WHY: the interesting bugs live *between* the pieces, in the
composition. The pieces can each be right and the whole still wrong.

## Assertions

Motoi ships `assert/invariants` and `assert/check-with` in the base
env. The exact semantics of these verbs are still being nailed
down; the pattern below shows the shape you can build without
special support.

```
(define (check name predicate value)
  (if (predicate value)
      (list 'pass name value)
      (list 'fail name value)))

(check 'money?
       (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'money)))
       (list 'money 'usd 100))
;; -> (pass money? (money usd 100))

(check 'money?
       (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'money)))
       100)
;; -> (fail money? 100)
```

`check` returns a value. A test harness can accumulate pass/fail
records and print a summary at the end.

<!-- NEEDS-ALFRED: Confirm the intended semantics of the frozen
     assert/* CORE verbs so this chapter can pin the recommended
     harness pattern. -->

## A tiny test harness

Here is an in-memory harness that runs a list of checks and
returns a summary.

```
(define (run-checks checks)
  (let loop ((in checks) (pass 0) (fail 0) (fails '()))
    (cond
      ((null? in)
        (list ':total  (+ pass fail)
              ':pass   pass
              ':fail   fail
              ':failed (reverse fails)))
      (else
        (let ((r (car in)))
          (cond
            ((eq? (car r) 'pass)
              (loop (cdr in) (+ pass 1) fail fails))
            (else
              (loop (cdr in) pass (+ fail 1) (cons r fails)))))))))

(run-checks
  (list
    (check 'is-money? (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'money)))
           (list 'money 'usd 100))
    (check 'is-money? (lambda (x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'money)))
           42)))
;; -> (:total 2 :pass 1 :fail 1 :failed ((fail is-money? 42)))
```

Two checks. One passes, one fails. The harness gives you a summary
with pointers to what went wrong. Wire that into your test suite
and the shape rules become tested regressions.

## Contracts on functions

A contract is a promise a function makes about its inputs and
outputs. In Motoi you can wrap a function so that its inputs are
checked before the body runs and its output is checked after.

```
(define (with-contract input-pred output-pred f)
  (lambda (x)
    (cond
      ((not (input-pred x))
        (list 'contract-violation 'input x))
      (else
        (let ((r (f x)))
          (cond
            ((not (output-pred r))
              (list 'contract-violation 'output r))
            (else r)))))))

(define (money? x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'money)))
(define (positive-money? m) (and (money? m) (> (caddr m) 0)))

(define double-money
  (with-contract money? positive-money?
    (lambda (m) (list 'money (cadr m) (* 2 (caddr m))))))

(double-money (list 'money 'usd 100))
;; -> (money usd 200)

(double-money 42)
;; -> (contract-violation input 42)

(double-money (list 'money 'usd 0))
;; -> (contract-violation output (money usd 0))
```

Doubling 0 gives 0, which fails the *output* contract. The
violation names *which side* — input or output — so debugging is
directed, not guessy.

Contracts are not free. Every call spends time on the checks. Use
them at *external* boundaries — code that touches the outside
world — and around code you don't trust. Don't wrap every internal
helper.

## Property-based checking

*Property-based* testing tests a property that should hold across
many inputs, not a specific input-output pair. For our allocation
function from Chapter 10:

- Property: `(math/sum (allocate T N)) = T` for any positive T and
  positive N.
- Property: every part is a non-negative integer.
- Property: no two parts differ by more than 1.

Motoi has `random-int` for generating test data. A tiny
property-based test:

```
(define (allocate total n)
  (let* ((base (quotient  total n))
         (rem  (remainder total n)))
    (let loop ((i 0) (out '()))
      (cond
        ((= i n) (reverse out))
        ((< i rem) (loop (+ i 1) (cons (+ base 1) out)))
        (else      (loop (+ i 1) (cons base out)))))))

(define (test-allocate-sums N-trials)
  (let loop ((i 0) (fails 0))
    (cond
      ((= i N-trials) (list ':trials N-trials ':fails fails))
      (else
        (let* ((total (+ 1 (random-int 100000)))
               (n     (+ 1 (random-int 10)))
               (parts (allocate total n))
               (sum   (math/sum parts)))
          (if (= sum total)
              (loop (+ i 1) fails)
              (loop (+ i 1) (+ fails 1))))))))

(test-allocate-sums 100)
;; -> (:trials 100 :fails 0)
```

100 random inputs. Zero failures. The property held on all 100
random tries — which is stronger evidence than one hand-picked
test.

Property-based testing is not a proof. But it catches the class of
bug where your test suite happens to only cover the cases you
thought of.

## Boundary tests

The bugs cluster at boundaries. Test the boundaries deliberately.

- 0
- 1
- -1
- Very small positive (1)
- Very large positive (near ceiling)
- Just below ceiling
- Just above ceiling
- Empty list
- Single-element list
- All-same list
- Missing value in the input
- Missing value at position zero
- Duplicate values

None of these are creative. All of them find bugs when the
straightforward middle-of-the-range test suite doesn't.

## Recap

- Verify at three levels: shape, constraint, invariant.
- Build a tiny check-and-report harness. Motoi lists are enough.
- Contracts on functions: check inputs and outputs at the
  boundary. Not every internal call.
- Property-based checks: test that a property holds across many
  inputs, not one.
- Boundary tests: 0, 1, -1, empty, ceiling, just-past-ceiling.
- The frozen `assert/*` CORE verbs will give a canonical harness
  when their semantics settle. For now, the shapes in this book
  give you what you need to write your own.

That is the book. Sixteen chapters. One doctrine repeated in as
many places as it applies. Money is not a scalar. Metrics carry
units. Values have shape. Everything you build on top of that
starts from a place where the interpreter, the tests, and the
future you have all been given a chance to catch the wrong thing
before it costs you.

Turn to the appendices for reference tables and cheat sheets.")

